1
00:00:12,660 --> 00:00:18,749
Hi, welcome to this session in the Independent Games Summit of the Game Developers Conference.

2
00:00:19,650 --> 00:00:23,737
We call this one, you have to stop working, even when you can't stop working.

3
00:00:24,739 --> 00:00:27,664
And I've spoken to many people throughout the years

4
00:00:28,265 --> 00:00:29,807
about crunch and burnout.

5
00:00:30,489 --> 00:00:32,993
And suffice to say, I'm not a fan. Do not recommend.

6
00:00:34,690 --> 00:00:38,414
I mean, none of us are. We just get stuck in it anyway, somehow, don't we?

7
00:00:38,434 --> 00:00:43,319
I had the idea for this panel because usually when we talk about crunching burnout in the

8
00:00:43,359 --> 00:00:48,284
broader game industry, the worst crimes against developers tend to be studio management ordering

9
00:00:48,324 --> 00:00:52,248
people in their power to work harder and burn themselves out faster.

10
00:00:53,269 --> 00:00:59,513
In the indie space, we can often burn ourselves out more joyfully, more enthusiastically,

11
00:00:59,673 --> 00:01:04,196
and more violently than any AAA worker because literally no one can stop us.

12
00:01:05,260 --> 00:01:07,181
Not legally, not physically, not emotionally.

13
00:01:07,241 --> 00:01:10,303
It's just us versus ourselves.

14
00:01:11,063 --> 00:01:15,166
So here are a few very experienced independent developers

15
00:01:15,226 --> 00:01:20,309
with different insights and strategies for how to avoid working yourself to death.

16
00:01:20,989 --> 00:01:24,532
You deserve a long career, my friend, making games,

17
00:01:25,452 --> 00:01:27,073
many, many games in the years to come.

18
00:01:27,233 --> 00:01:32,476
So please listen carefully to their survival strategies.

19
00:01:33,157 --> 00:01:33,437
Good luck.

20
00:01:34,470 --> 00:01:36,492
Hi everyone, I am Chandanayakanaika.

21
00:01:36,592 --> 00:01:38,353
I'm the co-founder and creative director

22
00:01:38,393 --> 00:01:39,974
of Outerloop Games here in Seattle.

23
00:01:40,595 --> 00:01:44,698
I've been in the game industry for almost 24 years.

24
00:01:44,718 --> 00:01:46,119
I was born in Sri Lanka,

25
00:01:46,459 --> 00:01:49,301
and my parents moved us when I was about eight years old

26
00:01:49,902 --> 00:01:52,083
during a civil war, going to Sri Lanka to the States.

27
00:01:52,764 --> 00:01:55,186
They, you know, they didn't feel comfortable

28
00:01:56,046 --> 00:01:56,707
us being there.

29
00:01:57,367 --> 00:01:59,869
Me, my brother, my sister, we were pretty young,

30
00:02:00,810 --> 00:02:02,471
and they wanted to have more opportunities for us.

31
00:02:03,290 --> 00:02:07,994
So we moved to the US, lived in Maryland, went to art school in Savannah, Georgia.

32
00:02:09,255 --> 00:02:11,897
And I watched my parents, you know, having to start over,

33
00:02:12,938 --> 00:02:13,918
moving to a whole new country.

34
00:02:13,999 --> 00:02:18,122
And I think I learned a lot of my work ethic from watching them

35
00:02:18,222 --> 00:02:21,144
see how hard they worked to provide for us.

36
00:02:21,905 --> 00:02:25,028
So I went to art school and then got a job at Bethesda at 19.

37
00:02:25,248 --> 00:02:26,249
Right place, right time.

38
00:02:27,770 --> 00:02:30,552
And I just did everything I possibly could.

39
00:02:30,592 --> 00:02:32,053
When someone asked me to do something, I did it.

40
00:02:33,046 --> 00:02:41,156
I felt like the only way I could get ahead in games was to just put, just, you know, throw myself onto it and do anything that it needed to get done.

41
00:02:41,196 --> 00:02:50,046
So I started in art, got into production, UI, trailers, design work, whatever needed to get done on the project, I was willing to do it.

42
00:02:51,468 --> 00:02:53,650
Eventually moved over to LA and Orange County.

43
00:02:54,394 --> 00:02:58,576
where I worked on a couple of Matrix titles for the movies that were coming out at the time.

44
00:02:58,717 --> 00:03:02,059
And then we eventually, after having our first kid, moved to the Seattle area,

45
00:03:02,659 --> 00:03:08,744
and we've been living there since. In my 20 years prior to starting Outerloop,

46
00:03:10,104 --> 00:03:13,747
I worked on a bunch of different games, and the team sizes varied from 10, 15, to

47
00:03:14,988 --> 00:03:21,733
150 to 200 people, depending on the project. And there was one commonality with all these,

48
00:03:21,753 --> 00:03:23,554
with the studios I worked at, was that

49
00:03:24,833 --> 00:03:26,614
The game had to ship, the game had to get done,

50
00:03:27,735 --> 00:03:33,318
and we needed to do whatever we could to help with that.

51
00:03:34,479 --> 00:03:35,659
It wasn't necessarily, you know,

52
00:03:35,699 --> 00:03:37,340
some places, depending on the time,

53
00:03:37,380 --> 00:03:39,081
there was a mandatory crunch,

54
00:03:39,181 --> 00:03:41,583
but most places it's not mandatory crunch.

55
00:03:41,643 --> 00:03:43,364
It's this more implied crunch.

56
00:03:44,284 --> 00:03:47,946
It's the scheduling, it's peer pressure from the team,

57
00:03:48,047 --> 00:03:50,788
or it's major deadline with the publisher,

58
00:03:51,288 --> 00:03:52,049
external pressure.

59
00:03:52,069 --> 00:03:52,189
It all.

60
00:03:54,438 --> 00:03:59,484
amounted in us working a lot of hours. I mean, there were times during work on Enter the Matrix

61
00:03:59,644 --> 00:04:06,572
that I put in 100-hour weeks because the game had to get done for the movies that were coming out,

62
00:04:06,712 --> 00:04:11,558
and that was a fixed date. So regardless of the issues we were having on the design side or

63
00:04:11,918 --> 00:04:12,359
production...

64
00:04:13,338 --> 00:04:17,180
just meant a lot of us were working a lot of hours. I mean, I would come home three in the morning,

65
00:04:17,820 --> 00:04:22,602
barely see my partner, get up in the morning, you know, for after a couple hours of sleep,

66
00:04:22,682 --> 00:04:26,804
and do it all over again. And that after a while, years of doing that just takes a huge

67
00:04:27,324 --> 00:04:32,566
mental and physical toll on your body. And when you're, you know, working that many hours,

68
00:04:32,586 --> 00:04:36,268
you're not being very productive. Like you can barely think of what's going on, you're making

69
00:04:36,288 --> 00:04:41,350
a lot of mistakes. It's just not healthy. And it's especially not healthy for the long term.

70
00:04:43,592 --> 00:04:46,854
So I've been doing that, having done that for 20 plus years,

71
00:04:46,934 --> 00:04:49,656
I decided that, you know, there must be a better way to do it.

72
00:04:49,897 --> 00:04:51,718
And I want to be able to spend more time with my partner,

73
00:04:51,738 --> 00:04:55,021
spend more time with my family and with my kids.

74
00:04:55,721 --> 00:04:59,184
So about four years ago, I started Outerloop as a fully remote studio.

75
00:04:59,704 --> 00:05:00,685
I think the timing was good.

76
00:05:00,745 --> 00:05:04,628
The tools and technology has gotten better with Zoom and Discord and Slack.

77
00:05:05,349 --> 00:05:08,271
We were able to, you know, myself and two other partners

78
00:05:08,331 --> 00:05:10,833
that I started the company with that I had worked with before,

79
00:05:10,853 --> 00:05:12,834
and we decided to try it remotely.

80
00:05:13,845 --> 00:05:15,047
And we all work out of our houses.

81
00:05:17,570 --> 00:05:21,494
It's grown from three people to four people to, you know, our first project was

82
00:05:21,534 --> 00:05:22,656
about nine when we shipped.

83
00:05:23,196 --> 00:05:26,881
I was still learning how to run a company and still doing too much.

84
00:05:27,141 --> 00:05:32,347
So there's like a responsibility and a work ethic that I, you know, I think I.

85
00:05:33,882 --> 00:05:37,082
I learned over the years, and some of the habits are really hard to make. I think a lot of my

86
00:05:37,122 --> 00:05:43,204
self-worth was tied into how productive I was being, which is not a healthy way to make anything

87
00:05:43,224 --> 00:05:50,146
or make a living. So over the years, I've learned to try to make myself more redundant, you know,

88
00:05:50,186 --> 00:05:55,527
hire people that we need to fill certain roles so that I'm not trying to do like eight different

89
00:05:55,547 --> 00:06:00,948
jobs that's been healthier, you know, and after having kids.

90
00:06:03,151 --> 00:06:06,071
we're forced to kind of budget our time better.

91
00:06:06,091 --> 00:06:09,372
You know, I wanted to see my kids' first steps

92
00:06:09,512 --> 00:06:11,213
and spend time with them as they grow up

93
00:06:11,233 --> 00:06:12,133
because they do grow fast.

94
00:06:12,173 --> 00:06:14,414
I mean, everyone tells you that kids grow fast,

95
00:06:14,454 --> 00:06:18,475
but oh boy, yeah, I mean, 14 years, 15 years

96
00:06:19,235 --> 00:06:22,376
with my two sons have gone by real quickly.

97
00:06:22,596 --> 00:06:27,058
So starting the studio remote was also just a decision

98
00:06:27,918 --> 00:06:30,099
for myself and my partner to spend more time

99
00:06:30,119 --> 00:06:31,339
with our family.

100
00:06:32,428 --> 00:06:36,409
And part of that is also making time for other things outside of games and staying away from

101
00:06:36,429 --> 00:06:42,090
the screen. So I coach sports. Before COVID, I would coach sports with both of my kids.

102
00:06:42,810 --> 00:06:45,251
And now that things are getting better in Washington, I'm doing that again.

103
00:06:45,271 --> 00:06:50,632
It's been really healthy, not just mentally, physically, to kind of stay away from the work

104
00:06:51,172 --> 00:06:57,554
side when I'm not working. Creatively, it's been a lot better, too, just to have that break to

105
00:06:57,594 --> 00:07:01,375
focus on something else. To solve problems, you kind of have to step away sometimes.

106
00:07:02,249 --> 00:07:07,912
It's made for a better work environment, a better family life balance, but it's a constant struggle.

107
00:07:08,452 --> 00:07:13,755
I'm pulled in constantly to think about like, how's the team doing? And you know, are we paying

108
00:07:13,795 --> 00:07:19,338
our bills on time? And everyone, you know, all that stuff. But I'm trying to shut off work when

109
00:07:19,358 --> 00:07:21,579
I'm not at work and focus on work when I am.

110
00:07:23,193 --> 00:07:24,413
The team is up to 15 now.

111
00:07:25,073 --> 00:07:29,035
We're spread across nine cities and 12-hour time differences.

112
00:07:29,115 --> 00:07:33,176
So we're definitely trying to find different ways for that to work.

113
00:07:35,517 --> 00:07:37,477
We're more empathetical for the different needs.

114
00:07:37,557 --> 00:07:39,898
Even though the COVID situation in the U.S. has gotten better,

115
00:07:39,938 --> 00:07:42,639
it's not the same in other parts of the world where our partners are.

116
00:07:44,139 --> 00:07:47,760
So over the last year, it's been really stressful on everybody, too,

117
00:07:47,860 --> 00:07:49,521
and make sure that people have time.

118
00:07:50,607 --> 00:07:55,577
We encourage mental health days. We encourage people to take minimum number of days off.

119
00:07:55,818 --> 00:07:57,561
They have to take a number of days off every year.

120
00:07:59,530 --> 00:08:04,114
We try to make sure, you know, check in on people more often, make sure they're doing well.

121
00:08:04,695 --> 00:08:08,698
And scheduling wise for the amount of work that's required, you know, we're trying to be better

122
00:08:08,718 --> 00:08:12,762
about that too, so that they're not feeling the same kind of pressures I did in my previous

123
00:08:12,802 --> 00:08:17,346
companies where I felt like I had to get stuff done because everyone else was doing. So I need

124
00:08:17,526 --> 00:08:25,233
myself as a, you know, studio head needs to be do a better job as an example for the rest of the team.

125
00:08:27,163 --> 00:08:31,827
We're also, the team is a little older, so you know, one of my partners had a baby recently,

126
00:08:31,867 --> 00:08:36,271
so we made sure that he had three, four months of paternity leave. And we plan around that,

127
00:08:36,291 --> 00:08:40,876
you know, we know that's a coming thing and we plan around it. So far it's been working out

128
00:08:40,896 --> 00:08:44,679
pretty well, but it's a constant struggle for myself to make sure that I'm not doing too much,

129
00:08:44,839 --> 00:08:48,002
which is easy habit to get back right into.

130
00:08:51,018 --> 00:08:55,680
So yeah, working for 24 hours, 24 years,

131
00:08:55,700 --> 00:08:59,121
well, I've learned a lot to what not to do,

132
00:08:59,582 --> 00:09:01,682
and it's really healthy,

133
00:09:01,823 --> 00:09:03,503
and it's better for the project and the team.

134
00:09:03,563 --> 00:09:04,784
If you can take the time,

135
00:09:04,804 --> 00:09:06,945
you definitely should take the time,

136
00:09:07,045 --> 00:09:09,466
and it's responsibility on the studio heads

137
00:09:09,766 --> 00:09:11,627
and the production team to make sure

138
00:09:11,667 --> 00:09:14,488
that the project is scheduled in a way that

139
00:09:15,431 --> 00:09:19,615
people's mental health and well-being are taken into account. That's the biggest part of making

140
00:09:19,656 --> 00:09:24,901
any game is the people. And if you're not taking care of yourself or your folks, then it's just

141
00:09:25,241 --> 00:09:30,988
in the long run, it's just not going to be healthy. And the products won't do as well,

142
00:09:33,450 --> 00:09:36,533
and neither will the studio. All right. Thank you.

143
00:09:38,257 --> 00:09:40,938
Hi, I'm Astrid. My pronouns are she, her.

144
00:09:41,378 --> 00:09:44,059
I'm CEO and co-founder of Triple Topping Games

145
00:09:44,199 --> 00:09:45,479
and advisor to Carbonites.

146
00:09:46,639 --> 00:09:48,240
Ever since we founded Triple Topping,

147
00:09:48,560 --> 00:09:50,341
it has been important for us to rethink

148
00:09:50,401 --> 00:09:53,322
how we structure work and allow ourselves to stop working.

149
00:09:54,382 --> 00:09:57,003
If you're curious on how we handle all this in details,

150
00:09:57,463 --> 00:09:59,024
you can always read our contract

151
00:09:59,064 --> 00:10:00,984
and employee handbook on our website.

152
00:10:02,065 --> 00:10:04,686
Before I start, I just want to give a small trigger warning,

153
00:10:04,906 --> 00:10:06,927
especially for those who are parents themselves.

154
00:10:08,351 --> 00:10:15,013
some context. To give the best understanding of my talk, I want to share a little bit of

155
00:10:15,073 --> 00:10:22,114
my current personal life situation. Last year, I gave birth to our baby Bobby. They were

156
00:10:22,154 --> 00:10:28,076
born premature week 34 with an emergency C-section. Since then, we have learned that Bobby most

157
00:10:28,156 --> 00:10:32,317
likely suffered from a chronical illness and we have spent countless hours at the hospital.

158
00:10:32,337 --> 00:10:36,498
I for the first time had to say no to things I planned.

159
00:10:37,402 --> 00:10:40,764
I even took a break from work from my work at Carmel Knights.

160
00:10:41,384 --> 00:10:46,206
But working is also what helped both my partner and I to focus on something else and allow

161
00:10:46,286 --> 00:10:48,367
ourselves to take a small break from the hospital.

162
00:10:49,428 --> 00:10:53,150
Socialize with other people and be creative and have a sense of normality.

163
00:10:54,070 --> 00:10:56,671
I'm thankful that I always practice to stop working.

164
00:10:57,312 --> 00:11:00,753
Otherwise, I would not in time have realized that that's what I had to do.

165
00:11:01,814 --> 00:11:04,895
I hope that the learnings I shared today can be helpful for others too.

166
00:11:07,045 --> 00:11:13,247
why it's hard to stop. Most people want to do the absolute best at any given job. On top of this,

167
00:11:13,327 --> 00:11:17,928
most people identify themselves by their profession and the job they do, especially

168
00:11:17,948 --> 00:11:24,289
in the games industry. This makes it incredibly hard to stop working. Personally, I don't believe

169
00:11:24,309 --> 00:11:29,630
in what I call the Netflix model. They share a handbook with no fixed amount of work hours.

170
00:11:30,530 --> 00:11:34,531
Because how do you know when to stop? What if your colleagues work more?

171
00:11:35,271 --> 00:11:38,013
Are you then lazy? Or maybe your boss thinks you are?

172
00:11:39,474 --> 00:11:44,277
I believe we need to help ourselves to stop. I believe we should all just agree on working

173
00:11:44,357 --> 00:11:50,761
less hours. Our industry combines conferences, parties, fun hangouts and discord and even

174
00:11:50,801 --> 00:11:57,005
rollerblades with our work. The lines between spare time and work are blurred. Game development

175
00:11:57,085 --> 00:11:59,327
are for some a lifestyle, not a job.

176
00:12:00,590 --> 00:12:03,010
It's our own way of coping with work-life balance.

177
00:12:03,431 --> 00:12:06,071
And it's a huge part of why I love this industry.

178
00:12:06,331 --> 00:12:09,793
But it also makes it so hard to stop working.

179
00:12:10,133 --> 00:12:13,014
I learned all this myself the hard way

180
00:12:13,074 --> 00:12:14,694
when I was expecting my first child,

181
00:12:14,854 --> 00:12:17,075
and once again when Bobby arrived.

182
00:12:17,775 --> 00:12:20,436
My love, care, and headspace were needed somewhere else

183
00:12:20,696 --> 00:12:22,196
than on our company Slack channel.

184
00:12:25,337 --> 00:12:27,758
Most of us have a hard time not to think

185
00:12:27,818 --> 00:12:29,198
about work in our spare time.

186
00:12:29,794 --> 00:12:31,555
It's because our work makes us worry.

187
00:12:32,276 --> 00:12:34,798
You worry about job role, the next deadline,

188
00:12:35,058 --> 00:12:36,119
that comment during lunch,

189
00:12:36,499 --> 00:12:38,381
if the CEO likes you or dislikes you,

190
00:12:39,101 --> 00:12:41,163
how to announce your pregnancy, et cetera.

191
00:12:42,183 --> 00:12:43,104
So to stop working,

192
00:12:43,204 --> 00:12:45,346
you also have to learn how to stop worrying.

193
00:12:45,686 --> 00:12:48,048
And I use this tool by advice from my dear brother.

194
00:12:49,349 --> 00:12:50,870
If it's not a problem in six months,

195
00:12:51,330 --> 00:12:52,111
it's not a problem now.

196
00:12:53,392 --> 00:12:58,253
Like running a studio, doing a job, life can be challenging and sometimes you're presented

197
00:12:58,314 --> 00:12:59,994
with a hill that seems too high to climb.

198
00:13:00,955 --> 00:13:03,556
To help myself, I think of challenging this way.

199
00:13:04,416 --> 00:13:08,297
Most things within six months from now have presented itself with a solution.

200
00:13:09,138 --> 00:13:11,779
A good or bad solution, but a solution.

201
00:13:12,939 --> 00:13:13,940
A break up right now.

202
00:13:15,552 --> 00:13:20,074
when it's happening, it can feel like the end of the world, but in six months you will start to

203
00:13:20,134 --> 00:13:26,637
move forward and see all the new positive changes in your life. It can also be a game release. In

204
00:13:26,698 --> 00:13:33,021
six months from now, the game is out. Maybe it will do amazingly, maybe not, but you will know and you

205
00:13:33,041 --> 00:13:38,044
will have the answer. Some things will not have presented itself with a solution in six months

206
00:13:38,064 --> 00:13:44,407
from now. Climate changes, for example. So we should worry about that. I even schedule winter

207
00:13:44,427 --> 00:13:44,607
spring.

208
00:13:45,532 --> 00:13:50,437
Very often your worries lie in the hands of other people, like a yes or no on funding.

209
00:13:51,318 --> 00:13:53,900
But until they give you that answer, stop worrying about it.

210
00:13:54,721 --> 00:13:57,964
I will also not allow myself to think about my worries before I sleep.

211
00:13:58,845 --> 00:14:03,789
It's hard and I practice it this every night, but I always tell myself a good story before I sleep.

212
00:14:04,109 --> 00:14:05,711
Sometimes I have to make it up.

213
00:14:07,028 --> 00:14:11,810
I know it's easy to tell you to stop worrying about work, especially going through a pandemic,

214
00:14:12,091 --> 00:14:15,713
many of us working alone from home, but it's always good to practice.

215
00:14:19,054 --> 00:14:20,155
How I stop working.

216
00:14:20,855 --> 00:14:22,236
Communication goes a long way.

217
00:14:22,656 --> 00:14:28,059
If you tell everyone when you are not working, it actually helps you to keep that promise

218
00:14:28,079 --> 00:14:28,760
to yourself too.

219
00:14:29,580 --> 00:14:33,182
So communicate to people when your work hours are.

220
00:14:33,882 --> 00:14:36,744
Let them know if you are on vacation and when you are back.

221
00:14:37,639 --> 00:14:40,280
Respect other people's time zones and office hours too.

222
00:14:41,221 --> 00:14:44,402
I put my work hours and time zones in my email footer.

223
00:14:44,643 --> 00:14:45,283
It helps a lot.

224
00:14:46,664 --> 00:14:47,864
Realize things can wait.

225
00:14:48,244 --> 00:14:50,405
No need to email a reply at 1 a.m.

226
00:14:50,746 --> 00:14:51,846
Other people are sleeping.

227
00:14:53,027 --> 00:14:54,447
Budget and plan for time off.

228
00:14:54,828 --> 00:14:55,608
Things take time.

229
00:14:55,948 --> 00:14:57,449
Game development, a long time.

230
00:14:57,989 --> 00:15:00,230
But try not to make a budget and time schedule

231
00:15:00,350 --> 00:15:02,511
that requires you to work 70 hours per week.

232
00:15:03,092 --> 00:15:04,873
It's like taking a loan on your own health.

233
00:15:05,353 --> 00:15:06,413
You can't keep doing it.

234
00:15:07,733 --> 00:15:12,074
Demand of your partner to be equal in parenthood, not only when it comes to weekends, but during

235
00:15:12,154 --> 00:15:12,794
work week too.

236
00:15:13,495 --> 00:15:15,555
My partner and I have worked every second day.

237
00:15:15,855 --> 00:15:20,336
It helped us to structure our work schedules and be 100% there for Bobby when they needed

238
00:15:20,356 --> 00:15:20,416
it.

239
00:15:21,196 --> 00:15:22,876
It made planning work-wise easy.

240
00:15:23,897 --> 00:15:25,717
Set goals and monitor your work time.

241
00:15:26,037 --> 00:15:29,738
Go from 50 to 40 or 40 to 35 hours.

242
00:15:30,458 --> 00:15:33,258
At some point, you'll get the same amount of work done in 32 hours.

243
00:15:34,812 --> 00:15:40,475
The benefit from this is also that if you need to work more, like towards a big deadline,

244
00:15:40,776 --> 00:15:46,640
a game release, for example, it would take a lot of extra work before you end up having

245
00:15:46,680 --> 00:15:47,620
to work long nights.

246
00:15:49,001 --> 00:15:54,545
Working towards a more healthy work life takes practice, but it's just as important as the

247
00:15:54,565 --> 00:15:55,245
game you are making.

248
00:15:58,244 --> 00:16:00,785
I know taking time off and working is a privilege.

249
00:16:01,586 --> 00:16:06,650
It requires you to have a secure job in the first place,

250
00:16:07,070 --> 00:16:11,113
to have sick pay, paid holiday, live in a welfare state,

251
00:16:11,614 --> 00:16:13,215
and you need to advocate your rights.

252
00:16:13,976 --> 00:16:15,937
Ironically, to be able to stop work,

253
00:16:16,517 --> 00:16:19,280
you need to have the resources to work.

254
00:16:20,661 --> 00:16:25,563
We are all in this together, but some of us have a lot more power than others.

255
00:16:26,404 --> 00:16:29,205
While I'm speaking from a small business perspective,

256
00:16:29,645 --> 00:16:33,147
the power for change lies at both ends of the spectrum.

257
00:16:33,807 --> 00:16:36,929
The small power I have to set an example or to advocate

258
00:16:37,349 --> 00:16:39,690
still needs to be met by the big corporations

259
00:16:40,190 --> 00:16:43,512
to build better working conditions, better publishing contracts,

