00:17:47,542 --> 00:17:51,926
I burnt out really hard last year while working for a wonderful US studio that had very little

276
00:17:51,966 --> 00:17:52,366
to do with it.

277
00:17:53,367 --> 00:17:57,311
I burnt out because time zone related overwork combined with having a toddler and the global

278
00:17:57,331 --> 00:18:02,115
pandemic to completely overwhelm the lifelong coping mechanisms I'd built up around undiagnosed

279
00:18:02,135 --> 00:18:02,356
ADD.

280
00:18:03,692 --> 00:18:07,493
I went from being a high-functioning person that relied on hyperfocus and random inspiration,

281
00:18:07,913 --> 00:18:13,334
to someone that was barely able to focus on anything and constantly failing to spot glaring errors in what I did manage to do.

282
00:18:14,434 --> 00:18:17,335
After a difficult conversation, I took a month off, then resigned.

283
00:18:17,895 --> 00:18:20,356
I really, really had to stop working.

284
00:18:21,076 --> 00:18:24,016
Things are much better now. I'm excited to be running a team and making a game,

285
00:18:24,477 --> 00:18:28,357
armed with the understanding of my ADD, good therapists, and support of an amazing partner.

286
00:18:29,057 --> 00:18:30,498
So, I'll be talking about two things.

287
00:18:31,171 --> 00:18:37,577
avoiding time zone stress, and how to get the most out of therapy. Sleep. Sleep is important.

288
00:18:37,937 --> 00:18:41,460
The major mechanism of time zone stress is a lack of or severely disturbed sleep.

289
00:18:41,901 --> 00:18:46,725
Bad sleep is a huge red flag. Remote working is great for flexibility, but working across

290
00:18:46,785 --> 00:18:51,449
time zones can get complex. It's normal to want to work with the people you work with.

291
00:18:52,124 --> 00:18:55,766
Not only is pure asynchronous communication difficult, but the times when you can chat

292
00:18:55,806 --> 00:18:59,328
directly to your co-workers and pair up on issues just feel so much more productive.

293
00:18:59,728 --> 00:19:04,771
Work hours tend to shift as a result. It usually starts out as just being up late or early for this

294
00:19:04,891 --> 00:19:09,313
one thing, which goes really well. Soon your work hours have shifted slightly to give you

295
00:19:09,353 --> 00:19:13,436
more overlap with your co-workers. Then meetings get scheduled for when you're always around.

296
00:19:14,716 --> 00:19:18,478
So to keep up the pace, you shift your day a little more. Spot the feedback loop.

297
00:19:19,076 --> 00:19:21,657
It requires constant effort to prevent time zone slippage.

298
00:19:22,018 --> 00:19:24,899
For some people, like me, it's nearly impossible to avoid,

299
00:19:25,119 --> 00:19:28,321
and we end up working a local night shift completely disconnected from where we live.

300
00:19:29,421 --> 00:19:32,783
In my case, that was a feature at first. Working remotely for a US studio meant I

301
00:19:32,823 --> 00:19:37,065
could look after our infant child and get work done all night. But as the child started

302
00:19:37,085 --> 00:19:40,167
sleeping through, the demands on my time meant I couldn't just sleep all day.

303
00:19:40,730 --> 00:19:44,032
Fast forward a couple of years and I was working in three distinct chunks every day,

304
00:19:44,152 --> 00:19:48,034
interspersed with hours of responsibilities in my regular time zone, and sleeping and eating

305
00:19:48,074 --> 00:19:53,157
in incredibly strange times. I was essentially experimenting with polyphasic work, and it felt

306
00:19:53,197 --> 00:19:58,520
like being jet lagged for months at a time. Cool, so that sucks. How do we not do that?

307
00:19:59,840 --> 00:20:04,003
Individually, you can counteract the pull into another time zone by focusing more on maintaining

308
00:20:04,043 --> 00:20:06,184
a constant starting time that's good for where you live.

309
00:20:06,792 --> 00:20:10,775
People will learn that you're always on at X time, but now that will work in your favor

310
00:20:10,856 --> 00:20:13,778
because they'll leave comms waiting for you or have quick handover meetings.

311
00:20:14,959 --> 00:20:17,421
Be reasonably ruthless about when you're not going to work.

312
00:20:17,861 --> 00:20:21,484
Sure, make yourself available for meetings and special things that need everyone's attention,

313
00:20:21,824 --> 00:20:24,667
but if you're doing those outside of what would be regular work hours for you,

314
00:20:24,987 --> 00:20:27,669
set time limits on those meetings and don't keep working afterward.

315
00:20:28,925 --> 00:20:31,927
Acknowledge that you're going to be working async a lot and plan around that.

316
00:20:32,187 --> 00:20:35,449
Make sure you always have tasks you can switch to if you get blocked on anything

317
00:20:35,489 --> 00:20:39,011
waiting for someone to get back to you. Be proactive about issues when they pop

318
00:20:39,031 --> 00:20:41,852
up and treat your pairing and co-working times as precious.

319
00:20:43,073 --> 00:20:45,814
Schedule and push for socializing time with your co-workers.

320
00:20:46,195 --> 00:20:49,557
This is fine to do outside regular work hours and be open to people wanting to

321
00:20:49,597 --> 00:20:51,598
socialize with you in their off hours as well

322
00:20:51,938 --> 00:20:53,819
because this doubles the time you have for connections.

323
00:20:54,974 --> 00:20:57,018
Monitor your time in more than just hours spent.

324
00:20:57,459 --> 00:20:59,182
Track your start and end times each day,

325
00:20:59,283 --> 00:21:00,786
spot trends, and watch for slippage.

326
00:21:01,227 --> 00:21:02,609
If you're routinely staying on through

327
00:21:02,629 --> 00:21:04,253
your co-workers' entire workdays,

328
00:21:04,633 --> 00:21:05,796
stop and take a breather.

329
00:21:07,303 --> 00:21:09,565
When it comes to running studios across multiple time zones,

330
00:21:09,865 --> 00:21:12,327
it's part of your responsibility to build systems that help

331
00:21:12,347 --> 00:21:14,409
your team members avoid time zone stress.

332
00:21:14,989 --> 00:21:17,691
This sounds obvious, but be aware of everyone's time zones.

333
00:21:17,992 --> 00:21:19,413
Build-in automatic do not disturbs

334
00:21:19,473 --> 00:21:21,074
based on when they don't want to be working.

335
00:21:21,455 --> 00:21:22,816
Respect their time when you schedule

336
00:21:22,836 --> 00:21:24,877
those inevitable meetings outside their workday,

337
00:21:25,278 --> 00:21:27,139
and if someone's obviously working later and later,

338
00:21:27,379 --> 00:21:28,220
check if they're okay.

339
00:21:29,421 --> 00:21:31,483
Plan far enough in advance that people are comfortable

340
00:21:31,543 --> 00:21:32,984
working asynchronously and picking up

341
00:21:33,064 --> 00:21:35,106
other tasks if they're blocked waiting for someone else.

342
00:21:36,293 --> 00:21:39,954
Treat that kind of waiting as a conveyor optimization task for yourself,

343
00:21:40,475 --> 00:21:42,676
rather than an availability problem on their part.

344
00:21:43,916 --> 00:21:47,498
Cut down on the concept of core hours that require everyone to be around.

345
00:21:47,998 --> 00:21:50,339
They're directly undermining your asynchronous capabilities.

346
00:21:50,919 --> 00:21:56,022
I get why core hours feel like a good idea, and you definitely do need some kind of occasional

347
00:21:56,102 --> 00:22:00,163
overlap so that important discussions can be had, but try to figure out ways to make those less

348
00:22:00,203 --> 00:22:00,443
frequent.

349
00:22:01,542 --> 00:22:03,404
And finally, commit to being remote.

350
00:22:03,965 --> 00:22:05,806
If some of your studio works at the same office,

351
00:22:06,147 --> 00:22:07,908
that's going to become the de facto time zone

352
00:22:07,928 --> 00:22:09,510
that everyone else is pulled towards.

353
00:22:09,990 --> 00:22:11,972
Part of this is making sure all your meetings can

354
00:22:11,992 --> 00:22:12,973
be caught up on the next day.

355
00:22:13,353 --> 00:22:14,815
You don't have to be minuting everything,

356
00:22:15,075 --> 00:22:17,397
but at least record decisions and expected outcomes.

357
00:22:18,698 --> 00:22:19,800
No time for a segue.

358
00:22:20,020 --> 00:22:21,181
On to the therapy cheat sheet.

359
00:22:22,447 --> 00:22:26,748
Therapy is a good thing. If there's one takeaway from my part of this talk, it's that you should

360
00:22:26,788 --> 00:22:31,669
go to therapy, even if it's only for a limited period, preferably well before you hit a situation

361
00:22:31,729 --> 00:22:35,870
like mine. The thinking that eventually got me looking for a therapist went something like this.

362
00:22:37,031 --> 00:22:41,692
What if I've frog-boiled myself into using up loads of resources just to function each day?

363
00:22:42,232 --> 00:22:46,273
What if there are other ways to exist that leave me less drained, and I can't see them from where

364
00:22:46,333 --> 00:22:51,134
I am now, but there are literally professionals that can help me figure this sort of stuff out?

365
00:22:51,917 --> 00:22:55,978
In my case, that led to an adult diagnosis of ADD, which has been incredibly helpful.

366
00:22:56,598 --> 00:23:01,220
Just understanding how and why I make decisions and how that differs from other people's mechanisms

367
00:23:01,460 --> 00:23:04,440
has alleviated so much stress and made running a team much easier.

368
00:23:06,141 --> 00:23:10,162
It's very important to know what you want from therapy. That can be catharsis, healing,

369
00:23:10,322 --> 00:23:14,703
new tools, self-knowledge, anything based on poking how you feel inside your own brain.

370
00:23:15,303 --> 00:23:18,364
It's not just the extremes of sobbing on the couch, which is perfectly okay,

371
00:23:18,804 --> 00:23:21,405
or some personification of a grinning self-help book on steroids.

372
00:23:22,239 --> 00:23:26,581
Different therapists prefer different approaches and patients. Finding a therapist is a lot like

373
00:23:26,681 --> 00:23:30,243
dating. You're going to need to meet a bunch of different people until you find someone

374
00:23:30,263 --> 00:23:34,026
that gels with you because therapists make that same call from their side as well.

375
00:23:34,906 --> 00:23:39,129
Also, please note that I'm coming at this from a privileged perspective in South Africa where I

376
00:23:39,169 --> 00:23:43,311
can both afford and choose therapists. Other people in my country don't have as many options

377
00:23:43,612 --> 00:23:46,353
and other countries' health systems restrict choice in other ways.

378
00:23:48,354 --> 00:23:53,018
It can be extremely exhausting to sit down with a person you've just met in a strange environment,

379
00:23:53,178 --> 00:23:56,762
pour parts of yourself out in front of them, and feel like they're just not engaging.

380
00:23:57,302 --> 00:24:01,486
Because they're not. A trained therapist will want to know as much about you and your situation as

381
00:24:01,506 --> 00:24:06,251
they can before they decide if they can indeed help or not. Until they know, they'll make extra

382
00:24:06,291 --> 00:24:08,133
sure they're not going to get in the way of anyone else.

383
00:24:09,613 --> 00:24:12,595
At the end of your first session with someone, if they think they can't help,

384
00:24:12,695 --> 00:24:17,797
they'll be extra distanced and disconnected. This isn't them judging you. It's them making

385
00:24:17,837 --> 00:24:21,279
sure they don't set anything in motion that another therapist won't know about.

386
00:24:21,960 --> 00:24:25,341
They really do want to help, so ask for recommendations for therapists they feel

387
00:24:25,401 --> 00:24:30,364
might work for you. Once you find a therapist you can work with, be prepared for things to take

388
00:24:30,464 --> 00:24:35,027
time. Very few therapists are going to recommend anything super impactful early on. It's mostly

389
00:24:35,067 --> 00:24:36,968
tests, questions, and trying out theories.

390
00:24:37,585 --> 00:24:43,987
You didn't get to where you are overnight, and your therapist first needs to figure out where that even is before you can start taking steps to move elsewhere.

391
00:24:44,428 --> 00:24:46,408
Thankfully, things add up over time.

392
00:24:47,709 --> 00:24:54,711
You're not obligated to keep seeing anyone that makes you uncomfortable, and you can always ask your therapist to stop any practices or methodologies for whatever reason.

393
00:24:55,251 --> 00:24:56,772
Therapy is about ongoing consent.

394
00:24:58,314 --> 00:25:02,317
Getting a diagnosis is a complex set of feelings to navigate, especially as an adult.

395
00:25:02,658 --> 00:25:05,860
It's important to know that you're still the same person and your life doesn't need to change

396
00:25:05,900 --> 00:25:11,304
drastically. You just know more about yourself. How you choose to use that knowledge is up to you,

397
00:25:11,585 --> 00:25:15,548
and you don't have to disclose any diagnoses to anyone else in your life if you don't want to.

398
00:25:16,268 --> 00:25:20,652
A diagnosis isn't a sentence or a proclamation about you. Most of the time, they're great for

399
00:25:20,692 --> 00:25:23,374
giving you a window into how the fuck other people do what they do.

400
00:25:25,264 --> 00:25:28,705
Medication isn't just something that happens. It's a com...

401
00:25:28,925 --> 00:25:31,926
Okay, hang on. Let's go into more depth about medication.

402
00:25:33,747 --> 00:25:36,528
Medication can only come from registered psychiatrists.

403
00:25:37,088 --> 00:25:40,329
Often, you'd be recommended to a psychiatrist by another therapist you're seeing.

404
00:25:40,950 --> 00:25:43,050
Psychologists can do diagnoses, but no meds.

405
00:25:43,531 --> 00:25:47,252
If someone that's not a psychiatrist recommends or offers medication, stay away.

406
00:25:48,798 --> 00:25:50,878
The choice to be medicated or not is up to you.

407
00:25:51,298 --> 00:25:53,119
Attitudes towards medication are complex,

408
00:25:53,159 --> 00:25:55,979
but the most important thing is how safe and empowered you feel.

409
00:25:56,419 --> 00:25:59,680
Additionally, please don't weigh in on anyone else's choice to medicate or not.

410
00:25:59,840 --> 00:26:00,380
That's gross.

411
00:26:01,840 --> 00:26:04,321
Psychiatrists issue medication.

412
00:26:05,181 --> 00:26:08,422
They're the pilot in a plane that's taking you to a destination of your choice.

413
00:26:08,982 --> 00:26:11,942
If you want to get off, they'll land it for you and help you pick a different flight.

414
00:26:12,422 --> 00:26:16,103
But self-medicating is a bit like hijacking a plane because your friend likes shrooms

415
00:26:16,623 --> 00:26:17,863
and has played a lot of flight simulator.

416
00:26:18,400 --> 00:26:24,483
don't do it. Should you choose to start medicating, know that the best approaches to medication are

417
00:26:24,563 --> 00:26:29,425
long-term. Nothing is a silver bullet. Yes, some people start meds and find that their situations

418
00:26:29,485 --> 00:26:33,927
change almost overnight, but if you've got a network of coping habits already, figuring out

419
00:26:33,987 --> 00:26:38,990
how and when those change due to medication takes time. A good psychiatrist will ease you into a

420
00:26:39,050 --> 00:26:43,332
medication gradually, letting you know what to expect and what to watch out for. It's perfectly

421
00:26:43,412 --> 00:26:47,014
okay to say, nope, I don't like how this impacts me and look for something else.

422
00:26:48,933 --> 00:26:52,274
Everyone's relationship with their meds is different and we get different things out of them.

423
00:26:52,834 --> 00:26:57,695
Sometimes meds are long-term interventions like glasses giving you a different perspective that you couldn't hold before.

424
00:26:58,376 --> 00:27:02,477
Other times meds are short-term like someone learning you a car so you can get back on your feet.

425
00:27:03,737 --> 00:27:08,278
Provided you're working with your therapist, there is no right or wrong way to be medicated or not.

426
00:27:09,399 --> 00:27:12,700
In fact, there is no right or wrong way to be full stop.

427
00:27:13,477 --> 00:27:17,818
Therapy is just a very good way to get someone else's expert input on how you are

428
00:27:18,359 --> 00:27:21,220
so that you can decide where to go next. You should try it.

