00:32:41,810 --> 00:32:43,813
when we like sort of rebranded Finji

526
00:32:44,034 --> 00:32:45,356
is we published a mission statement

527
00:32:45,396 --> 00:32:47,720
to hold ourselves, me and Adam, accountable.

528
00:32:48,441 --> 00:32:48,722
And like.

529
00:32:49,691 --> 00:32:51,612
It seems sort of light and fluffy or whatever,

530
00:32:51,672 --> 00:32:53,994
but there's a really important piece of it

531
00:32:54,014 --> 00:32:57,256
at the bottom, which is like, we practice inclusive team

532
00:32:57,296 --> 00:32:59,417
policies that support good quality of life,

533
00:32:59,858 --> 00:33:01,038
meaning no crunch.

534
00:33:01,619 --> 00:33:04,501
And we provide significant revenue shares or bonuses,

535
00:33:04,521 --> 00:33:07,943
however you want to use that word, for all team members.

536
00:33:09,484 --> 00:33:12,126
And that was written because we, Adam and I,

537
00:33:12,506 --> 00:33:14,187
needed to understand that we couldn't crunch.

538
00:33:15,328 --> 00:33:17,870
And we wrote this when we were parents of two young children.

539
00:33:19,918 --> 00:33:21,300
Now, like this was our deal with ourselves.

540
00:33:22,080 --> 00:33:23,382
And then we had to take that

541
00:33:23,422 --> 00:33:25,283
and make that same deal with our collaborators.

542
00:33:25,844 --> 00:33:27,065
So we have our FING policies

543
00:33:27,085 --> 00:33:28,646
where we work 40 hour work weeks.

544
00:33:29,207 --> 00:33:32,290
We have collaborator buy-in on short studio sprints,

545
00:33:32,410 --> 00:33:34,492
time zone overlaps per discipline and team

546
00:33:34,532 --> 00:33:36,253
to make sure we overlap in our working together.

547
00:33:36,634 --> 00:33:39,476
We have five planned weeks of studio closure every year

548
00:33:39,516 --> 00:33:40,157
that are paid.

549
00:33:40,637 --> 00:33:42,399
We have unlimited scheduled PTO.

550
00:33:42,419 --> 00:33:44,661
We have maternity leave and paternity leave benefits.

551
00:33:44,701 --> 00:33:46,102
We have six time, six.

552
00:33:46,582 --> 00:33:51,966
days, flexible work locations. We have weekends that don't belong to Fingy. We have comp time

553
00:33:52,006 --> 00:33:57,490
after travel and sprints. But I can say these things all day long, but it's just a promise.

554
00:33:58,031 --> 00:34:03,935
It's our job to follow our own policies and to be honest with ourselves. If we expect

555
00:34:03,975 --> 00:34:08,859
our teams to take time off, Adam and I have to take time off as well. We have to be intentional

556
00:34:08,959 --> 00:34:09,419
about this.

557
00:34:10,587 --> 00:34:11,487
So how do we do it?

558
00:34:11,587 --> 00:34:15,889
And this seems like an impossible problem in front of us.

559
00:34:15,969 --> 00:34:18,470
And we just took some really simple steps

560
00:34:18,490 --> 00:34:19,790
to sort of pull ourselves accountable.

561
00:34:20,490 --> 00:34:22,551
And the first thing is we have a production schedule

562
00:34:22,611 --> 00:34:25,212
and that seems obvious, but we have a schedule.

563
00:34:25,312 --> 00:34:27,153
We put things on it.

564
00:34:27,393 --> 00:34:28,173
We use it.

565
00:34:28,413 --> 00:34:29,614
We share it with the team.

566
00:34:30,154 --> 00:34:34,296
We schedule short-term, medium-term, long-term, 12 months from now.

567
00:34:34,557 --> 00:34:38,099
These are things that we have to do and they're going to change, but at least we

568
00:34:38,119 --> 00:34:43,882
have it written down so we understand the context of changes. We plan for and

569
00:34:43,902 --> 00:34:47,344
announce studio closures. We help the team wrap up projects or come

570
00:34:47,384 --> 00:34:50,786
to a reasonable pausing point before those studio closures. We actually have

571
00:34:50,846 --> 00:34:54,508
one in like two weeks. And studio closures means we don't work.

572
00:34:55,407 --> 00:34:58,448
Like yes, Discord lives on when we're not at work,

573
00:34:58,488 --> 00:35:02,410
but we also have admins that help us manage while we're on break.

574
00:35:03,370 --> 00:35:04,271
We have backup.

575
00:35:04,311 --> 00:35:07,732
So if somebody needs to go on vacation, we have somebody who can take over

576
00:35:07,792 --> 00:35:10,593
their spot if it needs to be taken over while they're gone.

577
00:35:12,994 --> 00:35:15,035
No, how else do we do it? We have communication rules.

578
00:35:15,555 --> 00:35:17,116
You know the saying about assume.

579
00:35:17,737 --> 00:35:19,658
Don't make an ass of me and you,

580
00:35:20,019 --> 00:35:21,379
or you and me, however you want to say it.

581
00:35:21,660 --> 00:35:23,461
We have to have collaborator buy-in.

582
00:35:23,501 --> 00:35:26,743
We can't have assumptions on how people are going to work.

583
00:35:27,304 --> 00:35:29,946
Your partners, your people that you live with,

584
00:35:30,246 --> 00:35:32,447
and your family, you can't assume

585
00:35:32,527 --> 00:35:34,149
that they're okay with what you're doing.

586
00:35:34,729 --> 00:35:35,530
They're probably not.

587
00:35:35,590 --> 00:35:36,490
Have you talked to them?

588
00:35:37,691 --> 00:35:39,272
You need to have buy-in from them.

589
00:35:39,432 --> 00:35:40,753
You need to have these conversations.

590
00:35:41,911 --> 00:35:44,132
We try to solve problems with solutions,

591
00:35:44,152 --> 00:35:47,134
and we tend not to discuss the merits of ideas or opinions,

592
00:35:47,194 --> 00:35:51,257
because those can let us bog down in valuing people

593
00:35:51,457 --> 00:35:53,499
rather than solving problems.

594
00:35:53,839 --> 00:35:56,541
And that's how we keep our design discussions

595
00:35:56,661 --> 00:35:59,543
and our to-do lists and task lists sort of on track.

596
00:36:01,664 --> 00:36:02,745
And then we write things down.

597
00:36:03,105 --> 00:36:04,706
We write down so much stuff.

598
00:36:04,766 --> 00:36:07,848
We have definitely discovered the value of documentation.

599
00:36:09,262 --> 00:36:10,664
And we also trust but validate.

600
00:36:11,164 --> 00:36:12,706
We have team one-on-one check-ins

601
00:36:13,847 --> 00:36:15,428
to see how our collaborators are doing.

602
00:36:16,209 --> 00:36:20,473
We also do validation for our tasks.

603
00:36:20,774 --> 00:36:24,177
So if we're gonna put something on a programmer's schedule,

604
00:36:24,237 --> 00:36:26,419
we need to understand how long this stuff is gonna take

605
00:36:26,439 --> 00:36:26,660
because...

606
00:36:27,060 --> 00:36:30,742
If you are wrong or wildly wrong, you didn't have that conversation,

607
00:36:31,043 --> 00:36:33,904
you may have assigned a 20-hour task when you thought it took two.

608
00:36:34,505 --> 00:36:40,329
And now you are setting someone up to fail and to not be able to take time to have that work-life

609
00:36:40,389 --> 00:36:40,769
balance.

610
00:36:42,638 --> 00:36:44,199
And we have constant collaboration,

611
00:36:44,219 --> 00:36:46,199
or not collaboration, we do that too.

612
00:36:46,440 --> 00:36:48,681
We have constant calibration that what we're working on

613
00:36:48,781 --> 00:36:50,822
is the right thing at the right time.

614
00:36:51,242 --> 00:36:53,403
Sometimes you need to punt things

615
00:36:53,483 --> 00:36:55,804
because you're going to get bogged down

616
00:36:56,064 --> 00:36:57,985
in something that doesn't have a solution yet.

617
00:36:58,345 --> 00:37:00,586
And we've gotten very comfortable with punting it forward

618
00:37:00,826 --> 00:37:03,748
and doing something that we can do in the time that we have.

619
00:37:06,109 --> 00:37:09,270
And we rely on these processes to keep us honest,

620
00:37:09,810 --> 00:37:10,771
honest with ourselves.

621
00:37:13,795 --> 00:37:21,701
Because we can't have Fingy and making things take over our entire life because we're more than what we create.

