691
00:42:53,600 --> 00:42:59,761
I remember working my late evenings, during my weekends and taking my laptop with me on my holidays.

692
00:43:00,601 --> 00:43:06,003
And at some point I even went back to taking Ritalin, which is a drug that helps you concentrate.

693
00:43:06,723 --> 00:43:11,924
It works well, but I knew it also made me nervous, depressed and more socially anxious.

694
00:43:12,744 --> 00:43:13,805
So, yeah...

695
00:43:15,054 --> 00:43:21,721
I also had moments when I was really deep into a project, like my website, and I really loved working on it.

696
00:43:22,242 --> 00:43:28,448
And I had a hard time stopping and thinking about it or doing other things.

697
00:43:29,789 --> 00:43:35,315
Although making my website gave me quite some energy, it drained way more in the end.

698
00:43:36,175 --> 00:43:40,518
There was a moment, and actually several smaller ones,

699
00:43:41,178 --> 00:43:43,939
where I just lost all confidence in what I had done

700
00:43:44,180 --> 00:43:46,181
and I really disliked the sight of my work.

701
00:43:47,561 --> 00:43:49,883
Looking back now, I did not take enough breaks

702
00:43:50,223 --> 00:43:53,865
and therefore didn't really have time to reflect on it.

703
00:43:54,705 --> 00:43:57,487
And being exhausted from continuously working

704
00:43:58,067 --> 00:43:59,608
did not help my mindset at all.

705
00:44:00,664 --> 00:44:05,006
If I had taken the distance I needed, I could have easily prevented these lower moments

706
00:44:05,566 --> 00:44:07,427
and stayed motivated towards the end.

707
00:44:10,108 --> 00:44:13,969
Currently, things with Simulant go at a very chill pace.

708
00:44:14,989 --> 00:44:17,771
Two reasons for that is that we just don't stress it.

709
00:44:17,791 --> 00:44:27,094
Taimen and I really like a chill workflow and also Taimen has to release a game every four months.

710
00:44:28,048 --> 00:44:32,571
So that creates an obligated break in the development every...

711
00:44:33,651 --> 00:44:35,773
Did I say two? I mean four months.

712
00:44:36,473 --> 00:44:42,597
So yeah, it creates a break, but it actually has been quite interesting and quite positively so.

713
00:44:43,798 --> 00:44:48,601
It gives us time to reflect and have a better perspective on the project.

714
00:44:49,241 --> 00:44:55,045
And therefore I think we made some better design choices and better art-related choices, in fact.

715
00:44:55,905 --> 00:45:01,508
I don't expect it to be completely crunch free, but I feel confident that it will manage

716
00:45:01,628 --> 00:45:02,669
any pressure quite well.

717
00:45:04,990 --> 00:45:11,993
And then I have to be frank and honest, because being crunch free is really hard, like I said,

718
00:45:12,193 --> 00:45:13,354
even when you really want to.

719
00:45:14,214 --> 00:45:20,917
And ironically, whilst making this talk, I've been actually experiencing a fresh little

720
00:45:20,977 --> 00:45:21,857
crunch just now.

721
00:45:22,872 --> 00:45:25,974
I really wanted to perform well and put a lot of pressure on myself.

722
00:45:26,715 --> 00:45:33,220
Besides, I really enjoy doing this. I've been working in evenings and in my free times and

723
00:45:33,400 --> 00:45:39,905
not taking enough breaks for some part. So actually breaking most of the rules I

724
00:45:40,045 --> 00:45:47,811
had written in the first place. On top of that, I thought this recording was due

725
00:45:48,712 --> 00:45:51,554
next week, the beginning of next week, but it was actually Friday.

726
00:45:52,687 --> 00:46:00,792
So what did I do? Nothing. I did nothing. So Tuesday I walked for several hours in a row.

727
00:46:01,372 --> 00:46:08,676
Then Wednesday I spent all time, all my time, or all the morning working at Boomhut because it's

728
00:46:08,717 --> 00:46:16,801
quite new and needs to be built still. And Thursday I went on to go climbing and work some other stuff.

729
00:46:18,440 --> 00:46:23,182
So, yeah, when I was working, I made sure I was taking enough breaks.

730
00:46:24,123 --> 00:46:31,587
And that little distance every time allowed me to have a better reflection on all I'd written and drawn.

731
00:46:32,987 --> 00:46:38,590
So, whether your continuous working style comes from a strong ambition, often like mine is,

732
00:46:39,651 --> 00:46:42,732
or a crunching deadline, crushing deadline,

733
00:46:44,573 --> 00:46:47,255
or an enthusiasm for the work you're doing.

734
00:46:48,763 --> 00:46:54,466
that makes it hard to stop, I present to you my ultimate list of things you can do.

735
00:46:55,687 --> 00:47:00,249
So the first thing I would say is you could keep track of your working hours.

736
00:47:01,050 --> 00:47:04,852
I've been doing this for one and a half years and

737
00:47:06,100 --> 00:47:10,507
I love this kind of data. It actually gave me a lot of insight on my behavior and style.

738
00:47:11,148 --> 00:47:18,038
Plus, it made me realize when I've been slacking off a bit, or actually working really hard when I felt I wasn't.

739
00:47:19,729 --> 00:47:25,552
I do this in Google Sheets and you can do it precisely as precise as you want, but in

740
00:47:25,592 --> 00:47:30,815
the end it's going to give you an overview of how many hours you work on something, what

741
00:47:30,835 --> 00:47:35,378
hours you tend to start and stop, and how efficient you're working.

742
00:47:36,879 --> 00:47:39,100
And that's also when you're making over hours.

743
00:47:40,381 --> 00:47:43,162
So I'm not the only one who does this.

744
00:47:43,562 --> 00:47:48,765
I actually got the idea by being inspired by my other game developer friends.

745
00:47:49,756 --> 00:47:52,958
Everyone that I know who does this would totally recommend it.

746
00:47:53,659 --> 00:47:59,904
It really helps with other things too, like making it easier to start working

747
00:48:00,584 --> 00:48:02,746
and making sure you have enough breaks.

748
00:48:04,647 --> 00:48:10,892
Then another tip I have for you is guard your weekends and evenings with your life.

749
00:48:11,873 --> 00:48:16,837
Seriously, I hear this over and over again and it's a very important thing to safeguard.

750
00:48:18,319 --> 00:48:22,382
Keep at least one hour before bed, solely for relaxing purposes,

751
00:48:23,643 --> 00:48:27,706
because you need time to wind down from your day and get a good rest.

752
00:48:28,847 --> 00:48:31,488
Not doing that will exhaust you very, very quickly.

753
00:48:32,789 --> 00:48:36,712
Then a thing you could do is work out a bit, you lazy bastards.

754
00:48:37,452 --> 00:48:40,835
I myself love to work, well, love to bother,

755
00:48:41,155 --> 00:48:44,297
no matter what deadline or how deep I'm into my work.

756
00:48:45,146 --> 00:48:50,193
I go two or three times a week, not because I'm a very fit or active person.

757
00:48:50,794 --> 00:48:51,976
Believe me, I'm not.

758
00:48:52,657 --> 00:48:57,884
But I found that it really helps my mind to get off things.

759
00:48:58,205 --> 00:49:00,889
And it's really nice for stress relief.

760
00:49:01,886 --> 00:49:08,947
So it also keeps you healthy and some other more smart people would tell you that's healthy too.

761
00:49:09,688 --> 00:49:19,510
So yeah, you could work out a bit and it doesn't really matter if you like to climb, run, swim

762
00:49:20,090 --> 00:49:25,231
or try at least to walk an hour a day and I'll tell you it helps a lot.

763
00:49:26,371 --> 00:49:31,052
And then what I find the most important one is to take breaks.

764
00:49:32,164 --> 00:49:35,066
Maybe every hour, but at least every two.

765
00:49:35,806 --> 00:49:40,109
Go outside for a walk, make yourself some tea, coffee,

766
00:49:40,649 --> 00:49:44,071
or in the evenings play a game, watch a series at night, read a book,

767
00:49:44,331 --> 00:49:45,332
find what works for you.

768
00:49:46,012 --> 00:49:49,054
But this not only gives your mind time to calm down,

769
00:49:49,595 --> 00:49:53,157
but it gives you a fresh look on your work when you're restarting it

770
00:49:53,957 --> 00:49:55,798
and dive back into it.

771
00:49:56,940 --> 00:50:04,503
If you still feel stress and you find yourself not relaxing and still working it out in your

772
00:50:04,563 --> 00:50:07,344
mind, it still helps a lot.

773
00:50:08,225 --> 00:50:14,347
And when things are really bad and you have a really, really hard time relaxing, try to

774
00:50:14,387 --> 00:50:21,110
go back to being in the moment, look at small things around you, try to listen to the noises

775
00:50:21,631 --> 00:50:26,253
and that helps me relax in even some really hard days.

776
00:50:27,824 --> 00:50:33,865
And on top of taking breaks being good for a busy mind,

777
00:50:34,965 --> 00:50:37,946
it's also most important for your work too,

778
00:50:38,966 --> 00:50:43,587
as it resets your focus and opens up space for a new idea

779
00:50:44,227 --> 00:50:48,188
and gives the necessary break for your mind, preventing total exhaustion.

780
00:50:49,128 --> 00:50:53,209
So I've been practicing these tactics for quite some time now.

781
00:50:54,217 --> 00:50:58,719
And although it's hard to remain totally crunch free, I think it's very possible.

782
00:50:59,419 --> 00:51:03,161
And I hope you try one of these tips and you'll find them useful.

783
00:51:04,401 --> 00:51:08,403
Anything? Anyway, it's time to take a break now.

784
00:51:09,223 --> 00:51:10,604
I think I'll leave these for you.

785
00:51:11,584 --> 00:51:13,225
And take good care.

786
00:51:13,765 --> 00:51:15,386
And thank you for listening.

